title_sort: louisa van velsor whitman to walt whitman, 23 september [1869]
title: Louisa Van Velsor Whitman to Walt Whitman, 23 September [1869]
text: â€”1869SeptrSeptember 23My dear waltWalti suppose you have arrived safe to your place of business as i have not had any news i conclude you are all right i hope none of them disagreabledisagreeable spelsspells has attacked you well walterWalter we are all about the same as when you left George didentdidn't come the day you left he wrote to me fridayFriday 17th but i didentdidn't get it till mondayMonday 20th saying he would not be home till the 1 of the month i kept the light burning all night saturdaySaturday night thinking he would come late but when i found he didentdidn't come i didentdidn't feel uneasy for i thought he couldentcouldn't leave i had a few lines from Jeffy this week they seem to be pretty well he said he wished you would write to him i have not much to write about Walter dear but i thought i had so many envelopes i could afford to use one of the small ones i may not write next week if i get your letter all right as i shall be pretty busy i may if i have any thing of importance to write i doodo hope you feel well waltWalt you must write about the new clerkold mrsMrs. turner next to where we used to live in this street died on the 20 is buried to morrow Louisa Van Velsor Whitman to Walt Whitman, 23 September [1869]
